docs.lead_paragraph: YELLOW FEVER IN NEW-ORLEANS--It seems to be an ascertained fact that the fever in New-Orleans would gradually disappear but for the constant arrivals of unacclimated persons, who will not been the official remonstrances of the authorities. The reports from the health Department show a decided diminution in the number of deaths of acclimated residents.

docs.lead_paragraph: The banquet and ball in aid of the Jews' Hospital in New-York at ?? Saloon last evening, was attended by at least 1,000 persons, who sat down at 7 o'clock to tables bountifully spread. BENJAMIN NATHAN, Esq., President of the Hospital presided at a table at one end of the room, at which also were seated Mayor THEMANN and other distinguished guests.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Emperor Napoleon has presented to the Empress' mother, Mine. de Montijo, the splendid mansion in the Champs-Elysees, lately purchased of he Marquis de Lauristan. The property is valued at 4,000,000 frames. The Emperor also gives it million of francs as his contribution to the dowry of Mile. Paniega, the future Duchess of Malakoff; while her Majesty superintends the preparation of the bride's ??.

headline.main: CENTRAL AMERICA.; Crops and Contracts in Costa Rica-The Proposed Confederation-Intelligence from Nicaragua. Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Panama Railroad Company's U. S. Mail steamship Columbus, Captain J. M. Dow, arrived at this port on the evening of the 6th inst. She brings dates from Guatemaia to Sept. 27, from Salvador to the 20th, from Realejo, Nicaragua, to Oct. 1, and from Costa Rica to the 3d. I am, as usual, indebted to Captain Dow for matters of interest that cannot be found in the newspapers of the different States.

docs.lead_paragraph: We have been favored with the perusal of a letter just received from this gentleman, concerning whom so much anxiety is felt. Mr. EISFELD is still in Fayal, and the state of his health prohibits the possibility of hisreturn this Winter. The terrible shock occasioned by the catastrophe to the Austria terminated in an inflammation of the lungs, under which Mr. EISFELD is still suffering.
